Singapore will be distributing free TraceTogether tokens nationwide from Sept 14, starting in the Jalan Besar and Tanjong Pagar districts.
The Government will also be starting a pilot programme requiring people to use either the free TraceTogether tokens or the app to check in at certain venues.
SMS alerts and a self-check service will also be launched from Sept 10 to inform people who were at places visited by Covid-19 cases.
Link in bio @straits_times
📸: Smart Nation and Digital Government Group

"Our overall advisory, it remains for everyone in Singapore, is not to travel, to avoid all travel," said National Development Minister Lawrence Wong during a virtual press conference yesterday.
It is unlikely that we will see improvement in the situation in the near term, which means that our travel advisory position is unlikely to change in the near term as well. added Mr Wong.
Link in bio @straits_times
📸: Alphonsus Chern
#coronavirus #covid19 #StraitsTimes

"Our overall advisory, it remains for everyone in Singapore, is not to travel, to avoid all travel," said National Development Minister Lawrence Wong during a virtual press conference yesterday.
It is unlikely that we will see improvement in the situation in the near term, which means that our travel advisory position is unlikely to change in the near term as well. added Mr Wong.
Link in bio @straits_times
📸: Alphonsus Chern
#coronavirus #covid19 #StraitsTimes

comments: @angeline_50  应该没可能去你的结婚礼

♻️ Got plastic and aluminium drink containers to recycle?
These "reverse" vending machines will dispense discount vouchers everytime you recycle bottles and cans.
Rewards include free rides with bike-sharing firm Anywheel, vouchers that can be used at CapitaLand malls, ActiveSG credit and Sentosa Fun Pass tokens.
There are now 50 of such vending machines islandwide at places such as IMM and Bedok Mall and complexes including the Toa Payoh and Jalan Besar Sports Centres.
If you're really serious about going green 🌱, you can also choose not to receive any rewards when you recycle at these machines.
Link in bio @straits_times
📸: Lim Yaohui
#gogreen #recycle #recycling #StraitsTimes

If you're really serious about going green 🌱, you can also choose not to receive any rewards when you recycle at these machines.

If you're really serious about going green 🌱, you can also choose not to receive any rewards when you recycle at these machines.
Link in bio @straits_times
📸: Lim Yaohui

These "reverse" vending machines will dispense discount vouchers everytime you recycle bottles and cans.
Rewards include free rides with bike-sharing firm Anywheel, vouchers that can be used at CapitaLand malls, ActiveSG credit and Sentosa Fun Pass tokens.
There are now 50 of such vending machines islandwide at places such as IMM and Bedok Mall and complexes including the Toa Payoh and Jalan Besar Sports Centres.
If you're really serious about going green 🌱, you can also choose not to receive any rewards when you recycle at these machines.

📸: Lim Yaohui

Rewards include free rides with bike-sharing firm Anywheel, vouchers that can be used at CapitaLand malls, ActiveSG credit and Sentosa Fun Pass tokens.
There are now 50 of such vending machines islandwide at places such as IMM and Bedok Mall and complexes including the Toa Payoh and Jalan Besar Sports Centres.
If you're really serious about going green 🌱, you can also choose not to receive any rewards when you recycle at these machines.
Link in bio @straits_times
📸: Lim Yaohui
#gogreen #recycle #recycling #StraitsTimes

These "reverse" vending machines will dispense discount vouchers everytime you recycle bottles and cans.
Rewards include free rides with bike-sharing firm Anywheel, vouchers that can be used at CapitaLand malls, ActiveSG credit and Sentosa Fun Pass tokens.
There are now 50 of such vending machines islandwide at places such as IMM and Bedok Mall and complexes including the Toa Payoh and Jalan Besar Sports Centres.
If you're really serious about going green 🌱, you can also choose not to receive any rewards when you recycle at these machines.

📸: Lim Yaohui

If you're really serious about going green 🌱, you can also choose not to receive any rewards when you recycle at these machines.

If you're really serious about going green 🌱, you can also choose not to receive any rewards when you recycle at these machines.

These "reverse" vending machines will dispense discount vouchers everytime you recycle bottles and cans.
Rewards include free rides with bike-sharing firm Anywheel, vouchers that can be used at CapitaLand malls, ActiveSG credit and Sentosa Fun Pass tokens.
There are now 50 of such vending machines islandwide at places such as IMM and Bedok Mall and complexes including the Toa Payoh and Jalan Besar Sports Centres.
If you're really serious about going green 🌱, you can also choose not to receive any rewards when you recycle at these machines.
Link in bio @straits_times
📸: Lim Yaohui

description:
♻️ Got plastic and aluminium drink containers to recycle?
These "reverse" vending machines will dispense discount vouchers everytime you recycle bottles and cans.
Rewards include free rides with bike-sharing firm Anywheel, vouchers that can be used at CapitaLand malls, ActiveSG credit and Sentosa Fun Pass tokens.
There are now 50 of such vending machines islandwide at places such as IMM and Bedok Mall and complexes including the Toa Payoh and Jalan Besar Sports Centres.
If you're really serious about going green 🌱, you can also choose not to receive any rewards when you recycle at these machines.
Link in bio @straits_times
📸: Lim Yaohui
#gogreen #recycle #recycling #StraitsTimes

If you're really serious about going green 🌱, you can also choose not to receive any rewards when you recycle at these machines.
Link in bio @straits_times
📸: Lim Yaohui

If you're really serious about going green 🌱, you can also choose not to receive any rewards when you recycle at these machines.

Rewards include free rides with bike-sharing firm Anywheel, vouchers that can be used at CapitaLand malls, ActiveSG credit and Sentosa Fun Pass tokens.
There are now 50 of such vending machines islandwide at places such as IMM and Bedok Mall and complexes including the Toa Payoh and Jalan Besar Sports Centres.
If you're really serious about going green 🌱, you can also choose not to receive any rewards when you recycle at these machines.
Link in bio @straits_times

Those engaging in strenuous exercise and children below the age of 2 will not be required to wear masks.
People may remove their masks when engaging in exercise such as running or jogging, but they must put it on afterwards, said National Development Minister Lawrence Wong.
The new measure takes effect immediately, and individuals who are caught refusing to wear a mask will be fined $300 on their first offence.
Singapore also reported 334 new coronavirus cases on Tuesday, bringing the total to 3,252.
Link in bio @straits_times
📸: Kua Chee Siong
#coronavirus #covid19 #StraitsTimes #SGUnited #StayHome

The new measure takes effect immediately, and individuals who are caught refusing to wear a mask will be fined $300 on their first offence.
Singapore also reported 334 new coronavirus cases on Tuesday, bringing the total to 3,252.
